00:01:31.570 --> 00:01:36.600
So the first one in
line is astigmatism,

00:01:36.600 --> 00:01:38.780
which is actually--

00:01:38.780 --> 00:01:42.240
for me, at least, it is the
most difficult to visualize.

00:01:44.870 --> 00:01:49.290
The best schematic I have seen
actually is in your textbook.

00:01:49.290 --> 00:01:51.300
It's the middle
picture over here.

00:01:51.300 --> 00:01:55.040
But before we get to that
and we see what happens

00:01:55.040 --> 00:02:00.810
is, let's define to make sure
that we know the terminology.

00:02:00.810 --> 00:02:07.500
So astigmatism happens--
look at the top left diagram.

00:02:07.500 --> 00:02:10.759
Astigmatism happens
with an object point

00:02:10.759 --> 00:02:14.130
that is off center.

00:02:14.130 --> 00:02:17.700
And since it is off center,
imagine that there's

00:02:17.700 --> 00:02:19.440
a fundamental asymmetry.

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:24.990
If you take the chief ray
that goes through the center

00:02:24.990 --> 00:02:25.890
of the lens--

00:02:25.890 --> 00:02:28.860
and again, here the assumption
is that the aperture

00:02:28.860 --> 00:02:30.720
is at the lens itself.

00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:35.010
So the chief ray goes to
the center of the lens.

00:02:35.010 --> 00:02:39.150
So now you can
take two ray-- you

00:02:39.150 --> 00:02:42.550
can think of two marginal rays.

00:02:42.550 --> 00:02:45.060
One is the marginal
ray that goes

00:02:45.060 --> 00:02:49.110
through the meridional plane.

00:02:49.110 --> 00:02:54.610
So the meridional plane is
the one shown like this,

00:02:54.610 --> 00:02:56.540
and the other is
the marginal ray

00:02:56.540 --> 00:02:59.580
that goes through the
sagittal plane, perpendicular

00:02:59.580 --> 00:03:02.820
to the meridional plane.

00:03:02.820 --> 00:03:08.310
So astigmatism occurs
because the two--

00:03:08.310 --> 00:03:11.890
now take cross-sections of
the rays in the two planes--

00:03:11.890 --> 00:03:14.540
the sagittal and the
meridional plane.

00:03:14.540 --> 00:03:17.670
That two ray bundles,
they do not necessarily

00:03:17.670 --> 00:03:18.870
focus at the same place.

00:03:21.510 --> 00:03:25.810
In the sagittal plane,
actually, if you

00:03:25.810 --> 00:03:27.650
tried to visualize it
in the sagittal plane,

00:03:27.650 --> 00:03:30.940
there is no difference
than normal incidence.

00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:31.860
So you basically get--

00:03:35.540 --> 00:03:38.380
so whereas in the meridional
plane, because you

00:03:38.380 --> 00:03:40.848
are off-axis, you
have this property

00:03:40.848 --> 00:03:42.390
that we discussed
before, that you'll

00:03:42.390 --> 00:03:47.410
get different magnification at
different points in the field.

00:03:47.410 --> 00:03:50.400
So as a result, these
two might actually

00:03:50.400 --> 00:03:52.660
yield different focal distances.

00:03:52.660 --> 00:03:55.680
So this is depicted here,
actually, where you're seeing--

00:03:55.680 --> 00:03:57.320
it's actually a
pretty good diagram.

00:03:57.320 --> 00:04:02.020
You can see the sagittal plane
and the meridional plane.

00:04:02.020 --> 00:04:06.630
And you can see that the
sagittal plane actually

00:04:06.630 --> 00:04:08.670
focuses out here.

00:04:08.670 --> 00:04:11.410
It is F sub S for sagittal.

00:04:11.410 --> 00:04:13.860
Whereas the meridional
plane focuses here.

00:04:13.860 --> 00:04:17.459
It is called F sub
T for tangential.

00:04:17.459 --> 00:04:21.060
So if an optical system is
subject to this problem,

00:04:21.060 --> 00:04:22.689
we just call astigmatic.

00:04:27.090 --> 00:04:29.820
The typical way that people
characterize astigmatism

00:04:29.820 --> 00:04:31.530
is with a spoke wheel.

00:04:31.530 --> 00:04:35.125
And most of you must
have taken eye exams.

00:04:35.125 --> 00:04:36.750
They give you a
similar test, actually,

00:04:36.750 --> 00:04:38.890
to test if your
eyes are astigmatic

00:04:38.890 --> 00:04:40.290
and you need correction.

00:04:40.290 --> 00:04:43.020
They show you something
like this, a spoke wheel.

00:04:43.020 --> 00:04:48.810
And they ask you, basically, if
the spokes are simultaneously

00:04:48.810 --> 00:04:57.040
in focus with the circle.

00:04:57.040 --> 00:05:00.330
The outline circle.

00:05:00.330 --> 00:05:04.440
So if the system
is astigmatic, then

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:09.910
as you move a piece of paper
along the optical axis,

00:05:09.910 --> 00:05:12.300
you will see one of them
come to a focus first,

00:05:12.300 --> 00:05:14.960
and the sagittal come
to the focus later.

00:05:14.960 --> 00:05:15.460
OK.

00:05:22.770 --> 00:05:23.880
So that's astigmatism.

00:05:30.430 --> 00:05:32.290
I hear some voices,
but I think they're

00:05:32.290 --> 00:05:34.820
from the next classroom,
not from Boston.

00:05:34.820 --> 00:05:38.120
Did anybody say anything there?

00:05:38.120 --> 00:05:38.850
I guess not.

00:05:38.850 --> 00:05:39.350
OK.

00:05:42.630 --> 00:05:48.040
A related aberration, which
has to do with the fact that--

00:05:48.040 --> 00:05:49.450
well, let me say first.

00:05:49.450 --> 00:05:52.840
So a related aberration is
called caricature of field.

00:05:52.840 --> 00:05:56.230
This one is actually
easy to understand.

00:05:56.230 --> 00:05:57.160
It says the following.

00:05:57.160 --> 00:06:01.660
It says that if you derive the
imaging condition for a point

00:06:01.660 --> 00:06:06.690
on-axis, then imagine
you go off-axis,

00:06:06.690 --> 00:06:10.680
it says that the image
may not necessarily

00:06:10.680 --> 00:06:18.650
focus on the same plane
as the image on-axis.

00:06:18.650 --> 00:06:22.100
In fact, what this
aberration is about

00:06:22.100 --> 00:06:28.780
is that the image actually comes
to focus on a curved surface.

00:06:28.780 --> 00:06:31.730
Center of the optical axis.

00:06:31.730 --> 00:06:33.350
Now, why do we care
about the plane?

00:06:33.350 --> 00:06:35.450
Why do we want this
to be a plane here?

00:06:35.450 --> 00:06:37.640
Well, in old
fashion cameras, one

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:41.470
used to put film at the
image plane of the camera.

00:06:41.470 --> 00:06:45.050
So we have to be sure that
the entire image is focused

00:06:45.050 --> 00:06:46.670
simultaneously on the film.

00:06:46.670 --> 00:06:48.050
Nowadays, we don't use film.

00:06:48.050 --> 00:06:51.200
We use a digital chip.

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:53.810
But in both cases, they're flat.

00:06:53.810 --> 00:06:55.580
So curvature of field
is a problem then

00:06:55.580 --> 00:07:04.770
because it says that actually
the off-axis image points will

00:07:04.770 --> 00:07:06.530
be out of focus
because they will focus

00:07:06.530 --> 00:07:08.387
in front of the final plane.

00:07:08.387 --> 00:07:10.470
So these are the kind of
things that if you could,

00:07:10.470 --> 00:07:14.688
for example, make a
curve chip surface,

00:07:14.688 --> 00:07:15.980
you could solve it immediately.

00:07:15.980 --> 00:07:19.610
All we have to do is match
the surface of the chip

00:07:19.610 --> 00:07:23.300
to the surface of the
curvature of the field.

00:07:23.300 --> 00:07:25.087
But in fact, actually,
people are trying

00:07:25.087 --> 00:07:26.170
to do something like that.

00:07:26.170 --> 00:07:28.570
There's a lot of work
on flexible electronics.

00:07:28.570 --> 00:07:31.340
And that's one of
the motivations.

00:07:31.340 --> 00:07:35.766
But it is not yet
widely available.

00:07:41.960 --> 00:07:45.050
Nevertheless, there
is one condition

00:07:45.050 --> 00:07:50.420
where the surfaces that the
field comes to focus actually

00:07:50.420 --> 00:07:51.640
becomes flat.

00:07:51.640 --> 00:07:53.720
This was derived
by a mathematician.

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:54.470
I don't know when.

00:07:54.470 --> 00:07:58.220
I think it was in
the early 1900s.

00:07:58.220 --> 00:07:59.660
His name is Petzval.

00:07:59.660 --> 00:08:03.680
So this condition, it has a
more complicated expression.

00:08:03.680 --> 00:08:07.100
But for two lenses, it works
out to something like this.

00:08:07.100 --> 00:08:12.560
If the sum of these
quantities where

00:08:12.560 --> 00:08:15.790
n1 is the index of
refraction of the lens.

00:08:15.790 --> 00:08:17.245
And f1 is the focal length.

00:08:17.245 --> 00:08:18.620
So it's a little
bit unusual now.

00:08:18.620 --> 00:08:21.950
We multiply the focal length
by an index of refraction.

00:08:21.950 --> 00:08:23.160
We've never done that before.

00:08:23.160 --> 00:08:25.520
But this is what
this guy derived.

00:08:25.520 --> 00:08:28.130
If they two sum up to
zero, these quantities

00:08:28.130 --> 00:08:35.360
for a pair of lenses, then the
field of curvature vanishes.

00:08:35.360 --> 00:08:44.430
And what is even more sort of
remarkable about this relation

00:08:44.430 --> 00:08:46.980
is that it does not involve the
space in between the lenses.

00:08:46.980 --> 00:08:52.430
No matter where they are, if
they satisfy this condition,

00:08:52.430 --> 00:08:56.530
the field of curvature
will be eliminated.

00:08:56.530 --> 00:09:01.390
And so for example,
if they are composed

00:09:01.390 --> 00:09:05.020
of the same index of refraction,
then the index of refraction

00:09:05.020 --> 00:09:07.430
also drops out of this equation.

00:09:07.430 --> 00:09:12.130
And then you can treat them as
a composite, as a thick lens,

00:09:12.130 --> 00:09:14.650
basically, which this is a
relationship that we already

00:09:14.650 --> 00:09:18.340
derived for a composite element.

00:09:18.340 --> 00:09:22.270
And you can make
sure that one of them

00:09:22.270 --> 00:09:27.370
is the negative of the other so
that you can make this quantity

00:09:27.370 --> 00:09:28.180
vanish.

00:09:28.180 --> 00:09:30.737
That is, f1 is
equal to minus f2.

00:09:30.737 --> 00:09:32.320
And then you can
find the focal length

00:09:32.320 --> 00:09:34.020
from this equation over here.

00:09:34.020 --> 00:09:37.360
So it's kind of cool because
it says that you can actually

00:09:37.360 --> 00:09:38.465
eliminate--

00:09:38.465 --> 00:09:39.840
if it is really
important to you,

00:09:39.840 --> 00:09:45.500
you can eliminate this problem
by using the Petzval condition.

00:09:45.500 --> 00:09:47.560
And again, there's a more
complicated condition

00:09:47.560 --> 00:09:50.380
that applies to
multilens systems that

00:09:50.380 --> 00:09:51.910
have more than two lenses.

00:09:51.910 --> 00:09:54.710
But I didn't bother
to draw it here.

00:09:54.710 --> 00:09:56.720
And what is even
more remarkable is

00:09:56.720 --> 00:10:00.950
that the Petzval surface
and the field curvature

00:10:00.950 --> 00:10:04.820
is also related to astigmatism.

00:10:04.820 --> 00:10:10.280
So what you see in this plot
here, also from the textbook,

00:10:10.280 --> 00:10:15.460
is the focal surfaces-- that is,
the surfaces in which different

00:10:15.460 --> 00:10:17.870
points from a flat--

00:10:17.870 --> 00:10:19.430
if you take a flat
object and you

00:10:19.430 --> 00:10:22.160
take different points
along this object,

00:10:22.160 --> 00:10:24.350
these three surfaces
are correspondingly

00:10:24.350 --> 00:10:27.860
the tangential focus for
the astigmatic system,

00:10:27.860 --> 00:10:37.450
the sagittal focus, and
finally the Petzval surface.

00:10:37.450 --> 00:10:38.920
Yeah.

00:10:38.920 --> 00:10:40.680
Let me go for [INAUDIBLE].

00:10:40.680 --> 00:10:44.090
So what we discussed here is
actually the Petzval condition.

00:10:44.090 --> 00:10:47.840
I haven't said yet what
is the Petzval surface.

00:10:47.840 --> 00:10:50.810
So the Petzval surface
is the following.

00:10:50.810 --> 00:10:54.770
It turns out that as
you change the stopping

00:10:54.770 --> 00:10:57.115
and optical system--
that is, as you move

00:10:57.115 --> 00:11:00.890
the stop in the
axial direction, you

00:11:00.890 --> 00:11:03.230
can achieve the condition
where the tangential

00:11:03.230 --> 00:11:06.350
and the sagittal
astigmatic focal

00:11:06.350 --> 00:11:10.100
surfaces, they collapse
into one surface.

00:11:10.100 --> 00:11:13.430
This surface is called
the Petzval surface,

00:11:13.430 --> 00:11:15.380
not to be confused with
the Petzval condition,

00:11:15.380 --> 00:11:18.120
even though, of course,
they are related.

00:11:18.120 --> 00:11:19.730
So what you see
here is basically,

00:11:19.730 --> 00:11:21.980
as you move the stop
in an optical system--

00:11:21.980 --> 00:11:25.325
this is borrowed from
another textbook, not from--

00:11:25.325 --> 00:11:26.700
I should have
recorded, actually.

00:11:26.700 --> 00:11:30.890
This is from Jenkins and
White, Fundamentals of Optics.

00:11:30.890 --> 00:11:35.510
So as you move the stop,
you can find the situation

00:11:35.510 --> 00:11:39.050
where the two surfaces coincide,
and that is the Petzval surface

00:11:39.050 --> 00:11:39.770
of the system.

00:11:39.770 --> 00:11:43.070
And of course, this one does not
satisfy the Petzval condition

00:11:43.070 --> 00:11:45.980
because the Petzval
surface is curved.

00:11:45.980 --> 00:11:50.150
If I could somehow satisfy
both the Petzval condition

00:11:50.150 --> 00:11:54.560
and collapse that to surfaces--
tangential and sagittal--

00:11:54.560 --> 00:11:59.210
onto the Petzval, then I
would have a flat system

00:11:59.210 --> 00:12:03.380
with a flat field, which would
also be free of astigmatism.

00:12:07.920 --> 00:12:13.540
So obviously we cannot get
into too much detail about this

00:12:13.540 --> 00:12:16.360
without becoming quantitative.

00:12:16.360 --> 00:12:19.910
And this is quite difficult
to deal with algebra,

00:12:19.910 --> 00:12:22.090
so I'm just being descriptive.

00:12:22.090 --> 00:12:23.900
And you will see some
of this in action

00:12:23.900 --> 00:12:30.820
when Se Baek does the demo of
the software in a little bit.

00:12:30.820 --> 00:12:34.367
And the light distortion
that I will discuss

00:12:34.367 --> 00:12:36.200
has to do with something
slightly different.

00:12:36.200 --> 00:12:40.240
So the field of curvature
occurs and astigmatism

00:12:40.240 --> 00:12:45.370
occurs because if you take
object points off-axis,

00:12:45.370 --> 00:12:47.990
they fail to focus
at the same plane.

00:12:47.990 --> 00:12:52.480
They focus at different planes
and on different surfaces,

00:12:52.480 --> 00:12:55.010
the sagittal and tangential.

00:12:55.010 --> 00:12:57.010
The distortion
occurs because even

00:12:57.010 --> 00:13:00.550
if you manage to
focus at one plane,

00:13:00.550 --> 00:13:02.200
the magnification is different.

00:13:02.200 --> 00:13:05.240
The magnification-- and this you
can see very easily, actually,

00:13:05.240 --> 00:13:08.710
just looking at this
diagram over here.

00:13:08.710 --> 00:13:12.510
If you take the on-axis point,
the imaging and condition

00:13:12.510 --> 00:13:15.520
of the magnification are
given by these distances.

00:13:15.520 --> 00:13:17.490
For example, the
lateral magnification

00:13:17.490 --> 00:13:22.040
is the ratio of this
distance to this distance.

00:13:22.040 --> 00:13:23.320
But what about this point now?

00:13:23.320 --> 00:13:26.900
For this point, the
lateral magnification

00:13:26.900 --> 00:13:31.670
will be the ratio of this
distance to this distance.

00:13:31.670 --> 00:13:33.890
And for those of
you in Boston, I'm

00:13:33.890 --> 00:13:38.290
pointing out to the
tilted chief ray.

00:13:38.290 --> 00:13:41.270
So I have to
measure the distance

00:13:41.270 --> 00:13:43.332
from the lens on the chief ray.

00:13:43.332 --> 00:13:45.290
And you can see very
easily that this length is

00:13:45.290 --> 00:13:47.690
different than the
length of the chief ray

00:13:47.690 --> 00:13:49.730
for the on-axis point.

00:13:49.730 --> 00:13:52.970
So because of that, the
magnification on-axis

00:13:52.970 --> 00:13:55.520
is different than the
magnification off-axis.

00:13:55.520 --> 00:13:59.240
Therefore, if I attempt
to image a checkerboard,

00:13:59.240 --> 00:14:02.720
like this, if the
magnification is different,

00:14:02.720 --> 00:14:10.410
I will see this sort of--

00:14:10.410 --> 00:14:12.540
I don't want to use
the word "distorted."

00:14:12.540 --> 00:14:15.530
You will see this
sort of altered--

00:14:15.530 --> 00:14:18.120
let's say altered-- image.

00:14:18.120 --> 00:14:20.250
And this is the
definition of distortion.

00:14:20.250 --> 00:14:22.440
So in optics we have
to be a little careful.

00:14:22.440 --> 00:14:25.020
Distortion, colloquially,
means everything.

00:14:25.020 --> 00:14:27.990
All of the stuff that
I described before.

00:14:27.990 --> 00:14:30.660
In everyday English, you
can call them distortions.

00:14:30.660 --> 00:14:32.760
Well, in optics, in
professional optics,

00:14:32.760 --> 00:14:37.080
when we mention distortion, we
automatically mean this one.

00:14:37.080 --> 00:14:39.420
So we have to be careful
not to use the word

00:14:39.420 --> 00:14:41.060
"distortion" in the
colloquial sense

00:14:41.060 --> 00:14:46.390
because it is reserved
to mean exactly that.

00:14:46.390 --> 00:14:50.170
And I guess it has two forms.

00:14:50.170 --> 00:14:53.350
It can be of this type,
where the magnification is

00:14:53.350 --> 00:14:55.300
higher off-axis.

00:14:55.300 --> 00:14:57.310
That is called pincushion.

00:14:57.310 --> 00:15:00.370
Or lower, that is called barrel.

00:15:00.370 --> 00:15:05.170
And they believe, in this case,
the top one will give rise

00:15:05.170 --> 00:15:10.420
to barrel because in this
case, because the stop is here,

00:15:10.420 --> 00:15:19.720
the aperture stop is here, the
chief ray on the object side

00:15:19.720 --> 00:15:22.470
becomes longer off-axis.

00:15:22.470 --> 00:15:24.820
Now, if you recall,
the magnification

00:15:24.820 --> 00:15:30.580
is the lateral
