we have this table, which
basically are lens data editor.

00:31:12.070 --> 00:31:14.740
So filling in this
table means you

00:31:14.740 --> 00:31:16.010
specify your optical system.

00:31:16.010 --> 00:31:18.210
I'll describe how to do it.

00:31:18.210 --> 00:31:19.570
But once you have this--

00:31:19.570 --> 00:31:21.580
once you fill in
this table, then you

00:31:21.580 --> 00:31:25.990
can analyze very
different stuff.

00:31:25.990 --> 00:31:30.890
So for example, it shows the
actual layout of a system,

00:31:30.890 --> 00:31:32.050
like this one.

00:31:32.050 --> 00:31:33.740
This 2D layout.

00:31:33.740 --> 00:31:39.200
And it even made the 3D
model for you, like this one.

00:31:39.200 --> 00:31:42.620
So it can check the actual
shape of the system.

00:31:51.800 --> 00:31:56.280
So this is called [INAUDIBLE].

00:31:56.280 --> 00:32:01.290
So actually, the horizontal axis
is actually your pupil plane,

00:32:01.290 --> 00:32:05.500
and vertical axis is deviation
of the ray at the image plane.

00:32:05.500 --> 00:32:06.720
So if you have--

00:32:06.720 --> 00:32:08.670
so if your system
is aberration free,

00:32:08.670 --> 00:32:11.460
then these lines should
be just horizontal here

00:32:11.460 --> 00:32:14.280
because all the rays
meet at the point.

00:32:14.280 --> 00:32:18.180
But this is practical system so
you have the deviation, which

00:32:18.180 --> 00:32:21.140
means you have aberration.

00:32:21.140 --> 00:32:28.780
And these guys are spot diagram.

00:32:28.780 --> 00:32:32.190
So if you have point object
in your object space,

00:32:32.190 --> 00:32:36.150
then you'll probably
get this kind of focus

00:32:36.150 --> 00:32:37.740
at your image plane.

00:32:42.300 --> 00:32:45.510
And this is same thing but
for different wavelengths

00:32:45.510 --> 00:32:49.320
because the glass
is dispersive, which

00:32:49.320 --> 00:32:53.482
means the refractive
index is also

00:32:53.482 --> 00:32:54.690
a function of the wavelength.

00:32:54.690 --> 00:32:59.280
So if you change the wavelength,
then the shape of these spots

00:32:59.280 --> 00:32:59.880
also change.

00:32:59.880 --> 00:33:04.680
So it analyzed this
dispersive property.

00:33:10.970 --> 00:33:12.340
OK.

00:33:12.340 --> 00:33:17.090
So let me explain how to
fit into those tables.

00:33:17.090 --> 00:33:20.210
So let's say we have
this two lens system.

00:33:20.210 --> 00:33:25.310
So what you do is you
just decompose your system

00:33:25.310 --> 00:33:26.930
to multiple surface.

00:33:26.930 --> 00:33:29.400
So for example, here
I have the object.

00:33:29.400 --> 00:33:32.300
So this is by
default surface zero.

00:33:32.300 --> 00:33:35.150
And the first surface
should be the front surface

00:33:35.150 --> 00:33:37.430
of the first lens here.

00:33:37.430 --> 00:33:43.610
And surface two is the back
surface of the first lens.

00:33:43.610 --> 00:33:46.580
And the surface three
is the front surface

00:33:46.580 --> 00:33:49.650
of the second lens,
and so on and so forth.

00:33:49.650 --> 00:33:53.720
So in the table we have the
different-- the multiple roles.

00:33:53.720 --> 00:33:57.380
So each role represent
the one surface.

00:33:57.380 --> 00:34:00.500
And the radius means the radius
curvature of the surface.

00:34:00.500 --> 00:34:04.640
So for example, here,
since this object is flat,

00:34:04.640 --> 00:34:07.390
the radius curvature
is infinity.

00:34:07.390 --> 00:34:10.449
And thickness is the
distance from the surface

00:34:10.449 --> 00:34:11.690
to the next surface.

00:34:11.690 --> 00:34:15.310
So in this case, d0 is
the distance from here

00:34:15.310 --> 00:34:16.780
to the first lens.

00:34:16.780 --> 00:34:20.380
And in some case, if you deal
with the infinite conjugate,

00:34:20.380 --> 00:34:24.400
like telescope, then
this d0 could be infinite

00:34:24.400 --> 00:34:27.760
because your object
is at infinity.

00:34:27.760 --> 00:34:30.879
And at the surface one,
I have the lens which

00:34:30.879 --> 00:34:33.400
has the radius curvature R1.

00:34:33.400 --> 00:34:34.600
So I have R1.

00:34:34.600 --> 00:34:39.310
And thickness d1 represent the
thickness of the actual length

00:34:39.310 --> 00:34:42.580
from here to here.

00:34:42.580 --> 00:34:45.699
And after the surface
one, I have the glass.

00:34:45.699 --> 00:34:51.060
So I just can specify the type
of glass, which is BK7 here.

00:34:51.060 --> 00:34:54.520
