00:38:22.650 --> 00:38:25.500
And the next example is actually
the Hubble Space Telescope.

00:38:25.500 --> 00:38:28.140
So Professor
Barbastathis already

00:38:28.140 --> 00:38:32.970
mentioned the last lecture
about this telescope.

00:38:32.970 --> 00:38:40.200
So actually, NASA realized after
they launched this telescope

00:38:40.200 --> 00:38:43.830
and find out the image is not
good as it's supposed to be.

00:38:43.830 --> 00:38:47.460
And they form a committee to
investigate what's the problem.

00:38:47.460 --> 00:38:52.450
And they eventually figured
out, and they fix it.

00:38:52.450 --> 00:38:55.300
But let's just start
with the structure here.

00:38:55.300 --> 00:39:00.810
So this is a typical
classic type telescope.

00:39:00.810 --> 00:39:02.760
We have two mirrors.

00:39:02.760 --> 00:39:04.800
So one is primary
mirror, which is

00:39:04.800 --> 00:39:09.600
a concave hyperboloid
mirror, and we

00:39:09.600 --> 00:39:14.070
have the secondary mirror, which
is convex hyperboloidal mirror.

00:39:14.070 --> 00:39:18.660
And the size of the mirror, the
diameter is about 2.4 meters.

00:39:18.660 --> 00:39:20.040
The primary mirror.

00:39:20.040 --> 00:39:25.860
And the second one is about,
I guess, 60 centimeters or so.

00:39:25.860 --> 00:39:30.300
And the distance between these
two mirror was 4.94 meters.

00:39:30.300 --> 00:39:33.240
So it's a huge telescope.

00:39:33.240 --> 00:39:37.240
And after extensive
investigation,

00:39:37.240 --> 00:39:43.080
the problem was, actually, the
shape of the primary mirror

00:39:43.080 --> 00:39:45.750
is not same as the
intended shape.

00:39:45.750 --> 00:39:47.680
So the overall shape--

00:39:47.680 --> 00:39:50.190
I mean, the curvature
of the mirror

00:39:50.190 --> 00:39:52.410
was slightly different
than the design.

00:39:52.410 --> 00:39:55.410
And it turns out
that even though--

00:39:55.410 --> 00:39:59.650
actually, the diameter of this
primary lens is 2.4 meter.

00:39:59.650 --> 00:40:04.550
But at the edge, the
difference between the design

00:40:04.550 --> 00:40:07.910
and the actual shape
was only 4 micrometer.

00:40:07.910 --> 00:40:13.110
So it's very small, the
physical difference.

00:40:13.110 --> 00:40:14.940
So just give you an idea.

00:40:14.940 --> 00:40:17.640
So the black hair,
like the Asians,

00:40:17.640 --> 00:40:20.990
like myself, the diameter
of the thick hair

00:40:20.990 --> 00:40:22.860
is about 100 micrometer.

00:40:22.860 --> 00:40:25.560
So 4 micrometer is
very, very small

00:40:25.560 --> 00:40:28.490
distance compared
to the diameter.

00:40:28.490 --> 00:40:32.340
But in general, it introduced
a huge speckle aberration,

00:40:32.340 --> 00:40:35.520
which means ideally you have--

00:40:35.520 --> 00:40:38.220
all these incoming rays
should meet at one point,

00:40:38.220 --> 00:40:41.900
but it has a different
extended focal point.

00:40:41.900 --> 00:40:47.250
So the effect was
too catastrophic.

00:40:47.250 --> 00:40:51.980
So the image of the galaxy
it looked like this.

00:40:51.980 --> 00:40:54.900
But after they fix,
it looked like this.

00:40:54.900 --> 00:41:03.510
So does anyone know how
NASA fixed this problem?

00:41:03.510 --> 00:41:05.100
The telescope was
already in orbit,

00:41:05.100 --> 00:41:07.020
so you cannot take it
back to the ground.

00:41:07.020 --> 00:41:13.310
And to fabricate another big
mirror also need huge resource.

00:41:13.310 --> 00:41:16.740
So how can you fix?

00:41:22.450 --> 00:41:22.950
Yeah.

00:41:22.950 --> 00:41:24.600
So actually what they did is--

00:41:28.100 --> 00:41:29.420
this is huge telescope.

00:41:29.420 --> 00:41:31.130
And they had a focal point.

00:41:31.130 --> 00:41:33.860
And they have different
cameras, because you

00:41:33.860 --> 00:41:38.030
deal with different spectrum,
like visible or the IR or UV.

00:41:38.030 --> 00:41:40.460
And what they did, actually--
and all these cameras

00:41:40.460 --> 00:41:42.600
show the same focal plane.

00:41:42.600 --> 00:41:45.710
So what they did, they actually
sacrificed another camera

00:41:45.710 --> 00:41:48.410
and put another
mirror system here

00:41:48.410 --> 00:41:51.800
to introduce this
speckle aberration

00:41:51.800 --> 00:41:54.380
but in opposite fashion.

00:41:54.380 --> 00:41:58.040
So they kind of canceled
the speckle aberration.

00:41:58.040 --> 00:42:10.780
So I prepared an example in
ZEMAX with the real parameter.

00:42:10.780 --> 00:42:16.000
So this is the intended design
of the Hubble Space Telescope.

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:18.850
And as you can see,
the surface number two

00:42:18.850 --> 00:42:20.440
and surface number
three, they are

00:42:20.440 --> 00:42:22.570
primary and secondary mirror.

00:42:22.570 --> 00:42:24.370
And this is
hyperboloidal mirror.

00:42:24.370 --> 00:42:35.140
So you have-- we have here.

00:42:35.140 --> 00:42:38.480
So conic coefficient.

00:42:38.480 --> 00:42:42.580
And this is the simulation
result if you have--

00:42:42.580 --> 00:42:44.440
simulation result
of image if you

00:42:44.440 --> 00:42:50.050
have the letter F. But
due to the manufacturing

00:42:50.050 --> 00:42:54.020
process, this conic
coefficient was not this one.

00:42:54.020 --> 00:43:01.360
So actually it was
negative 1.02324.

00:43:01.360 --> 00:43:05.180
So overall shape it
doesn't change that much.

00:43:05.180 --> 00:43:10.780
But the image analysis
looks very blurred.

00:43:10.780 --> 00:43:16.430
So that's why we had the
very blurred image of galaxy.

00:43:16.430 --> 00:43:20.105
And that's why you need to
deal with all these aberration

00:43:20.105 --> 00:43:23.410
with this computer software
because you can analyze

00:43:23.410 --> 00:43:25.020
easily and compensate easily.

00:43:28.750 --> 00:43:29.250
OK.

00:43:32.630 --> 00:43:35.610
So last example is optimization.

00:43:35.610 --> 00:43:39.320
So for example, let's
think about this one.

00:43:39.320 --> 00:43:42.860
I want to design some
optical system which

00:43:42.860 --> 00:43:45.540
has three lenses here.

00:43:45.540 --> 00:43:51.590
So these two positive lens
is made by crown glass,

00:43:51.590 --> 00:43:54.830
and this negative lens
is actually flint glass.

00:43:54.830 --> 00:43:56.570
And if you want to
design this one,

00:43:56.570 --> 00:44:01.250
then you have many
parameters you can tune.

00:44:01.250 --> 00:44:04.100
So the radius curvature
of each length--

00:44:04.100 --> 00:44:08.030
so R1/R2, R3/R4, and R5/R6.

00:44:08.030 --> 00:44:12.590
And also the thickness of the
lens, and also the distance

00:44:12.590 --> 00:44:13.760
between the lenses.

00:44:13.760 --> 00:44:16.650
So we have another
six parameters here.

00:44:16.650 --> 00:44:19.850
So you have total 12
parameters you can choose.

00:44:19.850 --> 00:44:26.270
And it's hard to find the best
parameter because you need

00:44:26.270 --> 00:44:30.430
some specification to satisfy.

00:44:30.430 --> 00:44:34.190
So what you do is you can just
run the optimization routine

00:44:34.190 --> 00:44:35.370
here.

00:44:35.370 --> 00:44:40.490
So first process-- first
procedure is select variable.

00:44:40.490 --> 00:44:43.610
As I just described,
you can tune the radius

00:44:43.610 --> 00:44:46.190
of curvature of the
lens and the thickness

00:44:46.190 --> 00:44:48.470
and the distance between lenses.

00:44:48.470 --> 00:44:51.670
So you want to choose the
variable you can tune.

00:44:51.670 --> 00:44:54.230
And this column, you
define the merit function,

00:44:54.230 --> 00:44:57.230
or sometimes it is called object
function or cross function.

00:44:57.230 --> 00:45:02.150
Basically, you just select
what you want to minimize.

00:45:02.150 --> 00:45:04.400
For example, you
want to minimize

00:45:04.400 --> 00:45:07.650
some speckle aberration
for given object point,

00:45:07.650 --> 00:45:12.580
or maybe you can
minimize a spot diagram,

00:45:12.580 --> 00:45:17.470
like size or focus for
different field points.

00:45:17.470 --> 00:45:21.590
And also, you can add some
constraint, like your total--

00:45:21.590 --> 00:45:25.160
physical system
should be like this.

00:45:25.160 --> 00:45:28.580
It cannot longer than
certain distance.

00:45:28.580 --> 00:45:31.760
Or the thickness of the
lens can be constrained due

00:45:31.760 --> 00:45:33.180
to the manufacturing process.

00:45:33.180 --> 00:45:36.440
So you can add some constraints.

00:45:36.440 --> 00:45:40.340
And then what you do is compute
the value of merit function

00:45:40.340 --> 00:45:43.430
with the different
combination of the parameter.

00:45:43.430 --> 00:45:46.940
And this is the automated--
this is iterative process

00:45:46.940 --> 00:45:49.082
so ZEMAX can do it for you.

00:46:03.860 --> 00:46:05.630
So this is the
layout of the system.

00:46:05.630 --> 00:46:08.870
I start with just
three each value--

00:46:08.870 --> 00:46:12.150
I just choose the
random value of this--

00:46:12.150 --> 00:46:13.990
I mean, there's 12 values here.

00:46:13.990 --> 00:46:16.400
So we have the
three lenses here.

00:46:16.400 --> 00:46:18.710
And parameter with
the [INAUDIBLE],,

00:46:18.710 --> 00:46:20.310
they are variables.

00:46:20.310 --> 00:46:22.040
So we have the 12
variables here.

00:46:26.040 --> 00:46:28.910
And this is the result
of the aberration

00:46:28.910 --> 00:46:31.940
at the initial state.

00:46:31.940 --> 00:46:36.490
And the spot diagram
through the focus.

00:46:36.490 --> 00:46:39.660
So as the bottom left figure,
I have four different incident

00:46:39.660 --> 00:46:40.160
angles.

00:46:40.160 --> 00:46:41.500
So 1, 2, 3, 4.

00:46:41.500 --> 00:46:43.440
The different colors here.

00:46:43.440 --> 00:46:47.400
So these four rows
in spot diagram

00:46:47.400 --> 00:46:53.550
means they're corresponding to
this different incident angle.

00:46:53.550 --> 00:46:58.550
And these five column means
I had five different defocus.

00:46:58.550 --> 00:47:02.210
So center one is focused,
and they are slightly

00:47:02.210 --> 00:47:03.530
defocused in front or back.

00:47:07.680 --> 00:47:12.040
I also have the spot diagram
with different wavelength.

00:47:12.040 --> 00:47:15.350
So this one is
about 500 nanometer.

00:47:15.350 --> 00:47:18.500
And it's about 480 nanometer.

00:47:18.500 --> 00:47:21.170
I guess this one is 550 or so.

00:47:21.170 --> 00:47:23.810
50 or so.

00:47:23.810 --> 00:47:31.870
And this is merit function.

00:47:31.870 --> 00:47:34.340
I already defined
the merit function.

00:47:34.340 --> 00:47:38.280
Actually, I used the default
merit function in this case.

00:47:38.280 --> 00:47:40.125
So there are many, many
different parameter

00:47:40.125 --> 00:47:43.146
you can tune, but
the essence is you

00:47:43.146 --> 00:47:45.790
want to minimize some
aberration at the image plane.

