01:00:04.820 --> 01:00:07.280
And he mentioned that the
motivation is basically

01:00:07.280 --> 01:00:11.660
that if you can focus
the light by using

01:00:11.660 --> 01:00:15.950
a non-uniform material,
a material whose

01:00:15.950 --> 01:00:20.570
index of refraction is variable,
perhaps you can get away

01:00:20.570 --> 01:00:23.600
by also using a material
whose surface is flat.

01:00:23.600 --> 01:00:27.080
So you don't have to use this
awkward spherical shape that we

01:00:27.080 --> 01:00:28.400
know from everyday optics.

01:00:28.400 --> 01:00:30.230
Maybe you can have
something that

01:00:30.230 --> 01:00:34.880
looks like a slab or a plate.

01:00:34.880 --> 01:00:38.100
And nevertheless, this
flat-looking plate

01:00:38.100 --> 01:00:40.850
might have the ability
to focus light.

01:00:40.850 --> 01:00:43.170
So the way you can
do-- first of all,

01:00:43.170 --> 01:00:44.430
can you do this kind of thing?

01:00:44.430 --> 01:00:47.910
Can you make an element with
variable index or the fraction.

01:00:47.910 --> 01:00:50.490
So there's two-- well,
there's many ways.

01:00:50.490 --> 01:00:53.840
But in industry, in
manufacturing practices,

01:00:53.840 --> 01:00:55.940
there's two ways
that are being used.

01:00:55.940 --> 01:00:58.690
And I will describe them.

01:00:58.690 --> 01:01:02.150
One is called ion exchange.

01:01:02.150 --> 01:01:05.440
And what they do is
they take a glass rod,

01:01:05.440 --> 01:01:08.560
which is doped with a
certain kind of ions--

01:01:08.560 --> 01:01:12.280
typically, they use
sodium in the glass rod.

01:01:12.280 --> 01:01:15.820
Then they have the glass meld
at the very high temperature,

01:01:15.820 --> 01:01:18.100
of course, with a
different kind of ion.

01:01:18.100 --> 01:01:19.810
Typically lithium.

01:01:19.810 --> 01:01:26.450
And what happens is they
slowly dip the glass rod

01:01:26.450 --> 01:01:28.240
into the glass meld.

01:01:28.240 --> 01:01:30.950
And over a period of several
hours, what's happens

01:01:30.950 --> 01:01:35.690
is the lithium ions, they kick
out some of the sodium ions

01:01:35.690 --> 01:01:36.710
from the glass rod.

01:01:36.710 --> 01:01:38.390
They basically
penetrate the rod,

01:01:38.390 --> 01:01:42.357
and they kick out some
of the sodium ions.

01:01:42.357 --> 01:01:43.940
But of course, the
index of refraction

01:01:43.940 --> 01:01:48.320
depends on what kind of ions
you have inside of the glass.

01:01:48.320 --> 01:01:52.070
And also, because the
ions, they propagate

01:01:52.070 --> 01:01:54.230
at a finite speed,
what will happen

01:01:54.230 --> 01:01:56.990
here is in the exterior
of the glass rod,

01:01:56.990 --> 01:01:58.490
you get a lot of ion exchange.

01:01:58.490 --> 01:02:00.470
So the index changes a lot.

01:02:00.470 --> 01:02:03.230
But near the center, if
you get your timing right,

01:02:03.230 --> 01:02:06.050
near the center you don't
get any exchange at all.

01:02:06.050 --> 01:02:07.730
So you basically have--

01:02:07.730 --> 01:02:10.730
in the center you
only have sodium ions.

01:02:10.730 --> 01:02:13.430
Near the exterior to give
both sodium and lithium.

01:02:13.430 --> 01:02:16.190
So you can get a situation
where the index of refraction

01:02:16.190 --> 01:02:21.750
is different in the center
than it is at the edge.

01:02:21.750 --> 01:02:24.310
And then what they
do, of course,

01:02:24.310 --> 01:02:25.860
is after they
finish this process,

01:02:25.860 --> 01:02:31.990
they chop this glass
rod into slabs.

01:02:31.990 --> 01:02:35.600
And then each one of those
slabs is to become a GRIN lens.

01:02:35.600 --> 01:02:37.800
And as I said before,
they do it typically

01:02:37.800 --> 01:02:41.250
so that the index is
higher in the center

01:02:41.250 --> 01:02:44.910
and lower at the edges.

01:02:44.910 --> 01:02:47.170
So this kind of thing I
will do in detail later.

01:02:47.170 --> 01:02:51.120
But if you look at
it in cross-section,

01:02:51.120 --> 01:02:54.540
it focuses like so
if you illuminate it

01:02:54.540 --> 01:03:00.090
with parallel bundle of rays.

01:03:00.090 --> 01:03:01.950
You can think of the
index of refraction

01:03:01.950 --> 01:03:04.740
as an attraction
of sorts for rays.

01:03:04.740 --> 01:03:08.070
So the ray that enters at
the lower index, it gets

01:03:08.070 --> 01:03:09.750
attracted by the high index.

01:03:09.750 --> 01:03:11.040
It bends.

01:03:11.040 --> 01:03:13.620
And as a result, by the
time the rays come out,

01:03:13.620 --> 01:03:16.340
they actually come out
as a focusing bundle.

01:03:16.340 --> 01:03:21.230
So you can use this
element to focus light.

01:03:21.230 --> 01:03:25.020
So just like a lens, but
it has a flat surface.

01:03:25.020 --> 01:03:30.690
And because the ionic change
is actually diffusion-driven--

01:03:30.690 --> 01:03:33.150
I don't want to go into the
mathematics of diffusion.

01:03:33.150 --> 01:03:40.050
But it turns out that if you get
the specific form of the index

01:03:40.050 --> 01:03:41.880
of refraction that
you get in this case,

01:03:41.880 --> 01:03:44.860
it's quadratic or parabolic.

01:03:44.860 --> 01:03:47.320
So it is maximum in the center.

01:03:47.320 --> 01:03:50.850
And then it drops
as the square--

01:03:50.850 --> 01:03:59.730
as the radius square, where r
is the radius in the slab times

01:03:59.730 --> 01:04:02.010
some coefficient alpha.

01:04:02.010 --> 01:04:05.760
And I will show in a second
that this coefficient alpha

01:04:05.760 --> 01:04:09.360
and the thickness of the
lens, the product of the two

01:04:09.360 --> 01:04:11.770
actually specifies
the focal length.

01:04:11.770 --> 01:04:13.350
So this looks like
a funny formula.

01:04:13.350 --> 01:04:15.930
But if you think
about it, alpha must

01:04:15.930 --> 01:04:19.560
have dimensions that
are inverse distance

01:04:19.560 --> 01:04:24.090
square so that the product
alpha times r squared

01:04:24.090 --> 01:04:25.740
is non-dimensional.

01:04:25.740 --> 01:04:26.920
And d is distance.

01:04:26.920 --> 01:04:29.490
So therefore, the units
here are distance.

01:04:29.490 --> 01:04:32.490
So indeed, the quantity
over there is the distance.

01:04:32.490 --> 01:04:35.920
It is the focal length.

01:04:35.920 --> 01:04:37.890
So let's see now why
this is the case.

01:04:41.650 --> 01:04:44.500
So I guess we've done
it several times.

01:04:44.500 --> 01:04:46.240
So you must be
tired of it by now.

01:04:46.240 --> 01:04:49.470
I just lost my--

01:04:49.470 --> 01:04:50.970
oh, maybe I'll use
the-- oh, thanks.

01:04:54.540 --> 01:04:56.222
I also must not forget this.

01:04:59.460 --> 01:05:00.500
OK.

01:05:00.500 --> 01:05:04.220
So in typical fashion, we
will use Fermat's principle

01:05:04.220 --> 01:05:07.410
in order to calculate
what is happening here.

01:05:07.410 --> 01:05:11.960
So Fermat says that if you--

01:05:11.960 --> 01:05:12.965
here is my element.

01:05:16.130 --> 01:05:21.360
And I have two rays that
both started at infinity.

01:05:21.360 --> 01:05:29.360
So the rays share their
origin, the starting point.

01:05:29.360 --> 01:05:33.680
And then my desire here,
my intended outcome,

01:05:33.680 --> 01:05:36.510
is that these two rays
meet because I want

01:05:36.510 --> 01:05:39.590
the element to focus the light.

01:05:39.590 --> 01:05:46.340
So Fermat says that the optical
path length here on-axis

01:05:46.340 --> 01:05:49.500
and the optical path
length out here off-axis,

01:05:49.500 --> 01:05:50.780
they must be equal.

01:05:50.780 --> 01:05:53.040
Because the rays started
at the same point,

01:05:53.040 --> 01:05:56.270
they end up at the same point,
the optical path lengths

01:05:56.270 --> 01:05:57.752
must be equal.

01:05:57.752 --> 01:05:59.210
So what is the
optical path length?

01:05:59.210 --> 01:06:03.570
So this derivation here is very
highly handwaving and very,

01:06:03.570 --> 01:06:05.150
very inaccurate.

01:06:05.150 --> 01:06:06.530
But bear with me.

01:06:06.530 --> 01:06:09.080
In the next half
hour, I will tell you

01:06:09.080 --> 01:06:12.200
how this calculation
can be done exactly.

01:06:12.200 --> 01:06:14.240
But for now, this is kind
of an interesting way

01:06:14.240 --> 01:06:16.540
to think about GRIN,
so we'll do it anyway.

01:06:16.540 --> 01:06:17.870
It's also in the book.

01:06:17.870 --> 01:06:20.720
So you don't really have
to copy my derivation here.

01:06:20.720 --> 01:06:22.530
You already have
it in two places.

01:06:22.530 --> 01:06:25.180
One is in the book, and
the other is the notes.

01:06:25.180 --> 01:06:28.550
So maybe you can just
look at it and don't

01:06:28.550 --> 01:06:30.770
bother to write it down.

01:06:30.770 --> 01:06:32.060
So let's compare the two rays.

01:06:32.060 --> 01:06:36.980
Let's compare the on-axis ray,
which basically goes straight.

01:06:36.980 --> 01:06:39.790
This is the optical axis.

01:06:39.790 --> 01:06:45.250
And the off-axis ray, which
as Pepe already mentioned,

01:06:45.250 --> 01:06:47.650
the off-axis ray will actually
do something like this.

01:06:47.650 --> 01:06:48.690
It will bend.

01:06:48.690 --> 01:06:50.940
And then, of course, after
it comes out in free space,

01:06:50.940 --> 01:06:52.330
it will go straight.

01:06:52.330 --> 01:06:53.620
We know that for sure.

01:06:53.620 --> 01:06:56.590
But inside the gradient index
medium, the ray will bend.

01:06:56.590 --> 01:07:05.390
It will follow a continuous
kind of trajectory.

01:07:05.390 --> 01:07:07.740
This is also counterintuitive
because in our experience

01:07:07.740 --> 01:07:09.550
light rays go straight.

01:07:09.550 --> 01:07:10.960
But such is life.

01:07:10.960 --> 01:07:13.720
Physics sometimes have
unexpected outcomes.

01:07:13.720 --> 01:07:16.450
If you put a ray in a
gradient index medium,

01:07:16.450 --> 01:07:20.900
indeed it will bend onto
a curved trajectory.

01:07:20.900 --> 01:07:22.850
So let's put some notation here.

01:07:22.850 --> 01:07:24.850
So we'll call this r.

01:07:24.850 --> 01:07:28.320
This is the radial direction.

01:07:28.320 --> 01:07:30.235
We'll call this d.

01:07:30.235 --> 01:07:33.190
This is the thickness
of the GRIN.

01:07:33.190 --> 01:07:34.420
We'll call this f.

01:07:34.420 --> 01:07:35.920
This is the focal length.

01:07:39.090 --> 01:07:43.050
And for the sake
of this derivation,

01:07:43.050 --> 01:07:45.570
let me actually redraw it.

01:07:45.570 --> 01:07:46.800
I will redraw it.

01:07:46.800 --> 01:07:49.080
Forgive me.

01:07:49.080 --> 01:07:53.208
I just want to emphasize
this caricature.

01:07:59.910 --> 01:08:03.460
So we'll actually
neglect this distance.

01:08:03.460 --> 01:08:06.480
This space over there, I
will pretend it's not there.

01:08:06.480 --> 01:08:10.580
And this is consistent with
a paraxial approximation.

01:08:10.580 --> 01:08:15.930
Here is r, here is d
again, and here is f.

01:08:15.930 --> 01:08:17.160
And that's the optical axis.

01:08:22.760 --> 01:08:23.260
OK.

01:08:29.130 --> 01:08:31.510
So well, let's do, first
of all, the optical path

01:08:31.510 --> 01:08:35.800
length for the on-axis ray.

01:08:35.800 --> 01:08:39.479
The optical path
length equals the index

01:08:39.479 --> 01:08:43.810
times the distance integrated
over the path of the ray.

01:08:43.810 --> 01:08:49.340
So this would equal the
index at radius equal 0.

01:08:49.340 --> 01:08:52.430
That is the index over
here at the center

01:08:52.430 --> 01:08:55.410
of the lens times the
thickness of the lens

01:08:55.410 --> 01:08:58.040
plus the focal length.

01:08:58.040 --> 01:09:01.399
So of course, outside the lens,
the index we assume to be 1.

01:09:01.399 --> 01:09:05.270
You can have an imaginary lens,
but let's not do that now.

01:09:05.270 --> 01:09:06.790
So this is where it comes from.

01:09:06.790 --> 01:09:07.630
AUDIENCE: Excuse me.

01:09:07.630 --> 01:09:08.630
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yeah?

01:09:08.630 --> 01:09:10.380
AUDIENCE: According
to Fermat's principle,

01:09:10.380 --> 01:09:13.340
it says that the ray
travels in such a way

01:09:13.340 --> 01:09:17.300
that it tries to
minimize the path.

01:09:17.300 --> 01:09:22.359
So why does the ray goes from
lower index to higher index?

01:09:22.359 --> 01:09:25.680
Means if it goes into
higher index material,

01:09:25.680 --> 01:09:29.020
actually it is increasing
its optical path length?

01:09:29.020 --> 01:09:30.020
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Ah.

01:09:30.020 --> 01:09:32.270
But it will bend.

01:09:32.270 --> 01:09:33.950
That's what Snell says.

01:09:33.950 --> 01:09:38.210
It will bend so that the total
path length actually decreases.

01:09:43.423 --> 01:09:45.840
Did I answer your question or
did you have something else?

01:09:45.840 --> 01:09:48.240
AUDIENCE: I think--
well, I don't know,

01:09:48.240 --> 01:09:52.120
but maybe the answer to your
question is that although--

01:09:52.120 --> 01:09:55.630
I think what he says is
that it will actually

01:09:55.630 --> 01:10:00.190
travel through a longer
optical path in the medium

01:10:00.190 --> 01:10:02.650
because it goes into
the bigger index.

01:10:02.650 --> 01:10:03.650
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Ah.

01:10:03.650 --> 01:10:04.150
OK.

01:10:04.150 --> 01:10:04.780
I see.

01:10:04.780 --> 01:10:08.050
AUDIENCE: But I think
that's counteracted

01:10:08.050 --> 01:10:12.280
by the extra that would be
outside, isn't it, in the air,

01:10:12.280 --> 01:10:12.780
I think.

01:10:12.780 --> 01:10:13.210
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS: Yeah.

01:10:13.210 --> 01:10:15.277
And you will see that
in the derivation.

01:10:15.277 --> 01:10:17.360
Because it will have to
go through this hypotenuse

01:10:17.360 --> 01:10:19.750
over here, it will
actually-- yeah.

01:10:19.750 --> 01:10:23.110
So the overall path
is actually minimized.

01:10:23.110 --> 01:10:25.487
And this is the only
way it can be minimized.

01:10:28.340 --> 01:10:28.840
OK.

01:10:28.840 --> 01:10:32.620
So lo and behold, then,
let's do what you just said.

01:10:32.620 --> 01:10:39.230
So what about the
ray that arrives

01:10:39.230 --> 01:10:41.240
at the higher elevation?

01:10:41.240 --> 01:10:43.470
So here I'm going
to cheat big time.

01:10:43.470 --> 01:10:45.980
I'm going to pretend
that all of this--

01:10:45.980 --> 01:10:48.530
the ray bends, of course.

01:10:48.530 --> 01:10:52.490
But I'm going to pretend that
throughout all this travel

01:10:52.490 --> 01:10:56.900
here, the ray sees the
same index of refraction.

01:10:56.900 --> 01:11:00.450
This is a gross approximation,
but I will do it.

01:11:00.450 --> 01:11:02.120
So therefore, this is--

01:11:02.120 --> 01:11:05.780
so n0, another name for it is--

01:11:05.780 --> 01:11:07.190
it is also equal to n max.

01:11:10.190 --> 01:11:14.448
The optical part for
n1 will be equal n max.

01:11:14.448 --> 01:11:18.690
1 minus alpha r
square over 2, which

01:11:18.690 --> 01:11:22.440
is the index of refraction
at the elevated position.

01:11:22.440 --> 01:11:24.870
And then, as you
pointed out, it will

01:11:24.870 --> 01:11:28.050
go through this increased
distance, which is

01:11:28.050 --> 01:11:32.760
the hypotenuse of the triangle.

01:11:32.760 --> 01:11:37.450
So it is really r
squared plus f squared.

01:11:37.450 --> 01:11:42.840
So again, I pretended that
this r and this r are the same.

01:11:42.840 --> 01:11:45.970
I want to emphasize that
this is an approximation.

01:11:45.970 --> 01:11:47.680
I'm cheating.

01:11:47.680 --> 01:11:50.340
OK.

01:11:50.340 --> 01:11:52.288
The next is actually
easier from now on.

01:11:52.288 --> 01:11:54.580
All I'm going to do-- and
the reason I'm going to do it

01:11:54.580 --> 01:11:56.070
is to remind you.

01:11:56.070 --> 01:11:58.650
I'm going to do the paraxial
approximation, which basically

01:11:58.650 --> 01:12:01.360
says that r is much less than f.

01:12:01.360 --> 01:12:06.720
So that means that square
root can be written as--

01:12:09.480 --> 01:12:12.000
I pull the f outside.

01:12:12.000 --> 01:12:17.040
1 plus r square over f
square approximately equal f1

01:12:17.040 --> 01:12:20.730
plus r square over 2f square.

01:12:20.730 --> 01:12:31.670
And this is actually equal
to f plus r square over 2f.

01:12:36.100 --> 01:12:42.430
So now let's write down
Fermat's principle.

01:12:42.430 --> 01:12:48.140
Fermat says that OPL 0
must be equal to OPL 1.

01:12:48.140 --> 01:12:56.650
So OPL 0 was n max
times d plus f.

01:12:56.650 --> 01:13:00.040
And OPL 1 was--

01:13:00.040 --> 01:13:02.890
again, if you look at
it from this equation,

01:13:02.890 --> 01:13:07.540
OPL 1 was this expression
times d, of course.

01:13:07.540 --> 01:13:09.670
I forgot to put the d here.

01:13:09.670 --> 01:13:12.190
Times this distance.

01:13:12.190 --> 01:13:21.010
So it is equal to n max 1 minus
alpha r square over 2 times

01:13:21.010 --> 01:13:25.510
d plus f plus--

01:13:25.510 --> 01:13:31.060
what was it-- r square over 2f.

01:13:31.060 --> 01:13:32.670
Now a number of
things will cancel.

01:13:32.670 --> 01:13:36.020
This will eat this one.

01:13:36.020 --> 01:13:39.750
This will eat this one.

01:13:39.750 --> 01:13:47.490
And all that is left is
that n max times alpha r

01:13:47.490 --> 01:13:56.130
square over 2d with a minus sign
plus r square over 2f equals 0.

01:13:56.130 --> 01:13:58.920
And now we can see that
the quadratic dependence

01:13:58.920 --> 01:14:01.080
for the index of
refraction that we draw

01:14:01.080 --> 01:14:04.290
is convenient because the
same quadratic came out

01:14:04.290 --> 01:14:07.570
of the paraxial approximation
of the square root.

01:14:07.570 --> 01:14:10.830
So I can just cancel
the two quadratics.

01:14:10.830 --> 01:14:13.470
And the twos also cancel.

01:14:13.470 --> 01:14:16.950
And I get that f
equals the inverse

01:14:16.950 --> 01:14:23.690
of all of that, 1 over n
max times alpha times d.

01:14:23.690 --> 01:14:26.600
This is how we find the
focal length of the GRIN.

01:14:26.600 --> 01:14:29.420
So this appears a little bit
mysterious what happened here.

01:14:29.420 --> 01:14:31.430
How did I pull this
out of the hat?

01:14:31.430 --> 01:14:32.640
Well, what it really means--

01:14:32.640 --> 01:14:35.180
the fact that this
has a solution

01:14:35.180 --> 01:14:39.260
means that this element
actually succeeds in focusing.

01:14:39.260 --> 01:14:40.650
What I mean is the following.

01:14:40.650 --> 01:14:42.800
Suppose that what came
out of this equation

01:14:42.800 --> 01:14:45.830
was not the nice quadratic
that canceled, but suppose

01:14:45.830 --> 01:14:46.950
I got something like this.

01:14:46.950 --> 01:14:51.680
Suppose I got minus n max
alpha r cube, for example,

01:14:51.680 --> 01:14:58.820
over 2 times d plus r
square over 2f equals 0.

01:14:58.820 --> 01:15:01.130
Well, if this is what I had
gotten, I'm out of luck.

01:15:01.130 --> 01:15:03.170
This is not a proper lens.

01:15:03.170 --> 01:15:04.940
So what I'm trying
to say is suppose

01:15:04.940 --> 01:15:09.020
that I made the GRIN
with a cubic dependence

01:15:09.020 --> 01:15:11.410
of the index of refraction,
another quadratic.

01:15:11.410 --> 01:15:14.030
Then this is the question I
would have arrived instead.

01:15:14.030 --> 01:15:16.580
Now I cannot cancel r anymore.

01:15:16.580 --> 01:15:21.140
So it means that each ray goes
to a different focal point.

01:15:21.140 --> 01:15:23.390
So therefore, this
element does not focus.

01:15:23.390 --> 01:15:27.560
So this would not
be a good lens.

01:15:27.560 --> 01:15:29.210
Actually, the cubic
dependence has

01:15:29.210 --> 01:15:31.250
some other interesting
properties,

01:15:31.250 --> 01:15:37.760
but these are perhaps for
a more advanced class.

01:15:37.760 --> 01:15:39.380
Nevertheless, the
quadratic dependence

01:15:39.380 --> 01:15:41.690
is very convenient
because as you can see,

01:15:41.690 --> 01:15:43.010
it drops out of here.

01:15:43.010 --> 01:15:45.500
It means that I have
a unique focal length

01:15:45.500 --> 01:15:47.960
at which all the
rays focus, at least

01:15:47.960 --> 01:15:49.610
in the paraxial approximation.

01:15:52.230 --> 01:15:56.100
So that is the story
of the quadratic GRIN,

01:15:56.100 --> 01:16:01.460
how it comes about, and how
we derive its focal length.

01:16:01.460 --> 01:16:05.000
And I should also say that
even though my derivation here

01:16:05.000 --> 01:16:10.500
was cheating,
basically the way I

01:16:10.500 --> 01:16:14.840
cheated is I assumed that d,
the thickness of the lens,

01:16:14.840 --> 01:16:16.250
is also very small.

01:16:16.250 --> 01:16:19.880
So it is very similar to
the thin lens approximation.

01:16:19.880 --> 01:16:23.090
Nevertheless, this equation
is actually true, even

01:16:23.090 --> 01:16:24.590
for thicker lenses.

01:16:24.590 --> 01:16:27.280
So that's kind of interesting.

01:16:27.280 --> 01:16:29.170
OK.

01:16:29.170 --> 01:16:32.380
The second way people make
GRIN optics is actually

01:16:32.380 --> 01:16:35.730
a combination of
melding and grinding.

01:16:35.730 --> 01:16:40.240
And the way they do that
results in a different profile

01:16:40.240 --> 01:16:46.450
that now the index of refraction
varies along the longitudinal--

01:16:46.450 --> 01:16:49.050
the axial dimension.

01:16:49.050 --> 01:16:51.460
So what does this mean?

01:16:51.460 --> 01:16:54.790
What they do first is
they start with a stack

01:16:54.790 --> 01:16:58.630
of glasses of different
indices over refraction.

01:16:58.630 --> 01:17:04.210
So here and in the rest of this
lecture, the sort of darkness

01:17:04.210 --> 01:17:06.020
indicates index of refraction.

01:17:06.020 --> 01:17:09.850
So dark gray means high index.

01:17:09.850 --> 01:17:12.520
Light gray means low index.

01:17:12.520 --> 01:17:14.470
So they stack them.

01:17:14.470 --> 01:17:17.050
Then they meld them,
which basically

01:17:17.050 --> 01:17:21.810
means that they mold and meld.

01:17:25.480 --> 01:17:29.400
So after they meld
them, basically

01:17:29.400 --> 01:17:31.300
the index of refraction,
the variation

01:17:31.300 --> 01:17:37.000
becomes kind of continuous
because as they meld,

01:17:37.000 --> 01:17:39.680
the different indices will
kind of diffuse into each.

01:17:39.680 --> 01:17:42.880
So you will get a
quasi-continuous variational

01:17:42.880 --> 01:17:43.930
index.

01:17:43.930 --> 01:17:47.290
And the final thing they
do is they actually polish.

01:17:47.290 --> 01:17:50.290
This stack that they've got with
a continuous index variation,

01:17:50.290 --> 01:17:51.913
they polish it.

01:17:51.913 --> 01:17:53.830
So now this thing actually
has two properties.

01:17:53.830 --> 01:17:55.950
First of all, it is a lens
in a traditional sense

01:17:55.950 --> 01:18:02.070
because it has a spherical
surface, so it focuses

01:18:02.070 --> 01:18:04.080
by virtue of refraction.

01:18:04.080 --> 01:18:07.390
But in addition, it has
an axial index profile.

01:18:07.390 --> 01:18:10.150
So here the
motivation is actually

01:18:10.150 --> 01:18:14.550
a little bit different than what
Pepe and I described earlier.

01:18:14.550 --> 01:18:18.550
So clearly I did not end up
with a slab-looking element.

01:18:18.550 --> 01:18:20.640
I still have a curvature.

01:18:20.640 --> 01:18:22.620
But the motivation is different.

01:18:22.620 --> 01:18:25.500
It's a little bit similar to--

01:18:25.500 --> 01:18:27.240
in the previous
lecture I think we

01:18:27.240 --> 01:18:30.780
mentioned something called the
Smith correction or the Smith

01:18:30.780 --> 01:18:32.220
telescope.

01:18:32.220 --> 01:18:33.900
So it's a very
similar motivation.

01:18:33.900 --> 01:18:40.200
If you take a
uniform index sphere,

01:18:40.200 --> 01:18:42.870
we saw this a couple of
times that in general, this

01:18:42.870 --> 01:18:49.230
produces an aberrated image,
even if it is oriented

01:18:49.230 --> 01:18:49.840
properly.

01:18:49.840 --> 01:18:53.340
This is supposed to be a
plane or convex lens oriented

01:18:53.340 --> 01:18:54.750
in the correct way.

01:18:54.750 --> 01:18:58.140
That is the plane wave goes
with the spherical surface.

01:18:58.140 --> 01:19:00.150
But still, this
does not completely

01:19:00.150 --> 01:19:01.160
cancel the aberration.

01:19:01.160 --> 01:19:04.390
There is still some residue.

01:19:04.390 --> 01:19:09.320
So what do you do then, if you
modify the index of refraction

01:19:09.320 --> 01:19:15.400
in the interior of the surface,
what happens is this ray--

01:19:15.400 --> 01:19:17.650
let's take the
paraxial ray over here.

01:19:17.650 --> 01:19:22.240
It hits at a relatively high
index, whereas this ray,

01:19:22.240 --> 01:19:25.300
it hits at a
relatively lower index.

01:19:25.300 --> 01:19:27.220
What this means,
if you want to look

01:19:27.220 --> 01:19:29.770
at it from the geometrical
optics point of view--

01:19:29.770 --> 01:19:32.740
there's also a wave optics point
of view that is interesting,

01:19:32.740 --> 01:19:34.855
but from the geometrical
optics point of view,

01:19:34.855 --> 01:19:37.420
it means that the
Snell's law of refraction

01:19:37.420 --> 01:19:42.610
here will be milder for
this ray than for this ray.

01:19:42.610 --> 01:19:46.570
Therefore, this ray, who's
used to focus kind of violently

01:19:46.570 --> 01:19:49.300
and produce a spherical
aberration here,

01:19:49.300 --> 01:19:52.570
now it will be pulled outwards.

01:19:52.570 --> 01:19:55.510
And therefore, it
will be forced to go

01:19:55.510 --> 01:20:00.130
through the proper focal point
over here as the paraxial lens.

01:20:00.130 --> 01:20:04.730
So this is a clever way to
fix spherical aberration.

01:20:04.730 --> 01:20:06.520
And I don't know who
invented this first.

01:20:06.520 --> 01:20:09.280
I believe-- and maybe, Colin,
you again correct with this.

01:20:09.280 --> 01:20:13.270
I believe in was Duncan
Moore at the Rochester

01:20:13.270 --> 01:20:17.520
who came up with
this particular--

01:20:17.520 --> 01:20:19.450
at least I've seen
a paper of his

01:20:19.450 --> 01:20:21.910
which is as old as
I am, 1971, that

01:20:21.910 --> 01:20:24.765
discusses this optimization.

01:20:30.250 --> 01:20:35.210
So in order to solve the
basic principles of GRINs,

01:20:35.210 --> 01:20:38.125
I would like to spend
a little bit of time--

01:20:38.125 --> 01:20:39.500
I don't think
we'll finish today.

01:20:39.500 --> 01:20:44.530
We'll probably have to leak into
next Wednesday after the quiz.

01:20:44.530 --> 01:20:50.350
But I'll get us started on, how
do we properly compute things

01:20:50.350 --> 01:20:51.220
like index?

01:20:51.220 --> 01:20:57.190
I mean, like focal length for
a gradient index structure.

01:20:57.190 --> 01:21:01.180
So we'd like to ask the
question more generally.

01:21:01.180 --> 01:21:06.250
If I have a medium whose
index of refraction

01:21:06.250 --> 01:21:08.590
varies as a function
of position.

01:21:08.590 --> 01:21:12.120
So here, this cloud is meant
to indicate a variable index.

01:21:12.120 --> 01:21:15.120
So you have high index, low
index, in different positions.

01:21:15.120 --> 01:21:18.330
So this is like a
generalized GRIN if you wish.

01:21:18.330 --> 01:21:19.370
We saw two types.

01:21:19.370 --> 01:21:23.070
You saw quadratic
and you saw axial.

01:21:23.070 --> 01:21:24.270
But it could be really--

01:21:24.270 --> 01:21:26.490
in principle, I should be
able to fabricate something

01:21:26.490 --> 01:21:26.990
like this.

01:21:26.990 --> 01:21:30.540
Not that it is readily
doable, but let's

01:21:30.540 --> 01:21:33.710
consider it for
the sake of value.

01:21:33.710 --> 01:21:35.340
So you've seen this
diagram before.

01:21:35.340 --> 01:21:37.560
In fact, I copied this
from an earlier slide.

01:21:37.560 --> 01:21:39.500
One of the previous--

01:21:39.500 --> 01:21:42.980
I think it was in the first
lecture or second lecture.

01:21:42.980 --> 01:21:46.490
So we don't know
really what path

01:21:46.490 --> 01:21:49.970
a ray will follow through
these variable index medium,

01:21:49.970 --> 01:21:51.050
but we know one thing.

01:21:51.050 --> 01:21:55.160
We know that if you integrate
this quantity, if you integrate

01:21:55.160 --> 01:22:00.530
the index of refraction
times the length,

01:22:00.530 --> 01:22:03.680
the elemental length
along the path of the ray,

01:22:03.680 --> 01:22:07.710
we know that Fermat requires
that these quantities will

01:22:07.710 --> 01:22:08.790
be minimized.

01:22:14.440 --> 01:22:17.940
So how do we deal with that?

01:22:17.940 --> 01:22:20.240
I mean, what can
we do about this?

01:22:20.240 --> 01:22:26.080
Now, some of you who have taken
advanced mechanics classes,

01:22:26.080 --> 01:22:29.010
this sounds a
little bit familiar.

01:22:29.010 --> 01:22:32.130
What is the name that
comes to mind when you

01:22:32.130 --> 01:22:33.790
see this kind of expression?

01:22:33.790 --> 01:22:35.310
So let me repeat again.

01:22:35.310 --> 01:22:37.740
I have a situation
where something--

01:22:37.740 --> 01:22:39.360
in this case, a
light ray, but it

01:22:39.360 --> 01:22:41.730
could be something
else, a particle

01:22:41.730 --> 01:22:45.243
or some mechanical analogy--

01:22:45.243 --> 01:22:47.160
can follow a number of
different trajectories.

01:22:47.160 --> 01:22:53.540
It can go this way or it can go
this way or this way and so on.

01:22:53.540 --> 01:22:55.840
To give you another
sort of trivial example,

01:22:55.840 --> 01:23:00.040
if I drop my marker here,
it goes down straight.

01:23:00.040 --> 01:23:03.540
So you may have wondered, well,
why does it go down straight?

01:23:03.540 --> 01:23:05.320
Why does it not do
something like this

01:23:05.320 --> 01:23:07.080
or like this or whatever?

01:23:07.080 --> 01:23:09.630
Why does it not go
up, for that matter?

01:23:09.630 --> 01:23:11.550
Well, it goes straight because--

01:23:11.550 --> 01:23:15.110
well, because gravity
pulls it down right.

01:23:15.110 --> 01:23:17.280
Well, we're very
happy with that.

01:23:17.280 --> 01:23:21.300
We know from experience
that things fall straight.

01:23:21.300 --> 01:23:23.310
But we also know that
gravity does not always

01:23:23.310 --> 01:23:25.260
produce straight trajectories.

01:23:25.260 --> 01:23:27.930
For example, the Earth.

01:23:27.930 --> 01:23:31.320
Thankfully, the Earth
follows a circular,

01:23:31.320 --> 01:23:34.657
or actually elliptical,
trajectory around the sun.

01:23:34.657 --> 01:23:36.990
And that's very fortunate
because if the Earth had a way

01:23:36.990 --> 01:23:38.970
to escape from the sun,
then we would all be--

01:23:38.970 --> 01:23:41.940
we would not even exist.

01:23:41.940 --> 01:23:47.510
So we know that gravity can
produce straight trajectories.

01:23:47.510 --> 01:23:52.520
It can produce
elliptical trajectories,

01:23:52.520 --> 01:23:56.530
hyperbolical trajectories,
and so on and so forth.

01:23:56.530 --> 01:24:00.250
So there's more to it
than the straight falling

01:24:00.250 --> 01:24:08.022
of the apple in Newton's case
or of the marker in my case.

01:24:08.022 --> 01:24:10.230
So anyway, so the reason
I'm giving all this preamble

01:24:10.230 --> 01:24:13.740
is because this may
be familiar for you

01:24:13.740 --> 01:24:16.470
from the field of mechanics.

01:24:16.470 --> 01:24:18.960
And the buzzword
that comes to mind

01:24:18.960 --> 01:24:22.590
when you have this kind of
integral with something inside

01:24:22.590 --> 01:24:26.620
and you demand that the
integral itself is maximized

01:24:26.620 --> 01:24:28.440
is Lagrangian.

01:24:28.440 --> 01:24:32.910
It is the Lagrangian principle
that you may have seen.

01:24:32.910 --> 01:24:37.655
I don't think those of
you took 2003 saw it.

01:24:37.655 --> 01:24:39.030
Did you or did
you not, actually?

01:24:39.030 --> 01:24:41.390
I don't know.

01:24:41.390 --> 01:24:43.225
Is anybody in the
class who took 2003?

01:24:43.225 --> 01:24:46.000
You should because
2004 is a prerequisite.

01:24:46.000 --> 01:24:47.500
And as a principle,
if you are here,

01:24:47.500 --> 01:24:57.120
it means you have taken
both 2003 and 2004.

01:24:57.120 --> 01:25:02.523
We have lost our undergraduates,
or they lost their voice,

01:25:02.523 --> 01:25:03.440
or they're too sleepy.

01:25:03.440 --> 01:25:05.615
Anyway.

01:25:05.615 --> 01:25:07.240
Or there's another
possibility, that we

01:25:07.240 --> 01:25:13.550
don't remember if we were
taught Lagrangians in 2003.

01:25:13.550 --> 01:25:15.610
Anyway.

01:25:15.610 --> 01:25:16.860
But I will not do it this way.

01:25:16.860 --> 01:25:20.760
So it turns out I can solve
this problem using a Lagrangian

01:25:20.760 --> 01:25:21.820
formulation.

01:25:21.820 --> 01:25:23.070
But I will not do it this way.

01:25:23.070 --> 01:25:25.420
Did someone want to speak?

01:25:25.420 --> 01:25:26.420
I saw the camera moving.

01:25:26.420 --> 01:25:29.785
Was someone about to speak?

01:25:29.785 --> 01:25:31.410
AUDIENCE: I was just
going to say, yes,

01:25:31.410 --> 01:25:32.680
we did have Lagrangian.

01:25:32.680 --> 01:25:34.060
GEORGE BARBASTATHIS:
Ah, you did.

01:25:34.060 --> 01:25:34.560
OK.

01:25:34.560 --> 01:25:36.221
Thank you.

01:25:36.221 --> 01:25:37.155
Thank you.

01:25:42.120 --> 01:25:44.440
Well, even if you did,
I guess I will not

01:25:44.440 --> 01:25:47.230
do it with the Lagrangians
because, well, the math is

01:25:47.230 --> 01:25:54.080
too complicated and would
kind of cause a detour here.

01:25:54.080 --> 01:25:56.250
Nevertheless, I will use
a mechanical analogy.

01:25:56.250 --> 01:25:58.850
So for a moment, we'll
take a break from optics.

01:25:58.850 --> 01:26:02.660
And I guess to
justify why 2004 is

01:26:02.660 --> 01:26:06.800
a prerequisite for this
class, I will show this.

01:26:06.800 --> 01:26:09.350
And I will spend, I guess,
the next 15 or so minutes

01:26:09.350 --> 01:26:12.410
to establish a connection
between this mechanical system

01:26:12.410 --> 01:26:14.940
and light rays.

01:26:14.940 --> 01:26:16.905
For now, let's forget
about light rays.

01:26:16.905 --> 01:26:19.860
I've given you-- it's
actually a particle.

01:26:19.860 --> 01:26:22.570
So it looks like a car
but it's really small.

01:26:22.570 --> 01:26:25.590
So I don't have to worry
about moments of inertia

01:26:25.590 --> 01:26:28.480
and all of that stuff.

01:26:28.480 --> 01:26:31.720
It is also frictionless, so
I don't have any dissipation

01:26:31.720 --> 01:26:33.440
at all in the system.

01:26:33.440 --> 01:26:36.400
This particle is
attached to a rigid--

01:26:36.400 --> 01:26:43.660
to an immobile, rigid
wall with a spring.

01:26:43.660 --> 01:26:45.520
And basically what
I can do is I can

01:26:45.520 --> 01:26:49.870
inject some energy into the
particles by pulling it.

01:26:49.870 --> 01:26:53.620
So if I do that, then
we know that this system

01:26:53.620 --> 01:26:56.860
has two forms of energy.

01:26:56.860 --> 01:26:59.530
When I actually pull
it, what I do is I

01:26:59.530 --> 01:27:02.410
store energy in the spring.

01:27:02.410 --> 01:27:05.530
The spring is not happy
having its energy stored.

01:27:05.530 --> 01:27:07.450
It will want to give it away.

01:27:07.450 --> 01:27:09.900
What does it mean to
give away the energy?

01:27:09.900 --> 01:27:11.470
It means to convert
it to kinetic.

01:27:11.470 --> 01:27:15.250
It means the spring will start
pulling the particle back.

01:27:15.250 --> 01:27:18.340
As the particle is pulled
back, it will accelerate.

01:27:18.340 --> 01:27:20.480
It will reach a
maximum velocity--

01:27:20.480 --> 01:27:23.320
we know that from
classical mechanics--

01:27:23.320 --> 01:27:28.210
approximately where the
spring has zero displacement.

01:27:28.210 --> 01:27:29.770
And at this point,
all of the energy

01:27:29.770 --> 01:27:32.170
has been converted to kinetic.

01:27:32.170 --> 01:27:34.868
And of course it will not stop
there because it is moving,

01:27:34.868 --> 01:27:36.160
and there's nothing to stop it.

01:27:36.160 --> 01:27:37.630
It will keep moving.

01:27:37.630 --> 01:27:39.190
But if it moves,
now it is beginning

01:27:39.190 --> 01:27:41.740
to push, to squeeze this spring.

01:27:41.740 --> 01:27:44.830
So now the particle is
giving back its energy

01:27:44.830 --> 01:27:48.900
into the spring until all of
the energy has been given.

01:27:48.900 --> 01:27:50.760
Now the spring is squeezed.

01:27:50.760 --> 01:27:52.020
Doesn't like to be squeezed.

01:27:52.020 --> 01:27:56.100
It starts giving energy
back to the particle.

01:27:56.100 --> 01:27:57.810
And of course, on
and on they go.

01:27:57.810 --> 01:28:00.810
This will execute and
oscillate in motion

01:28:00.810 --> 01:28:07.210
forever because I
neglected all dissipation.

01:28:07.210 --> 01:28:09.490
And of course, what is
happening in this case is

01:28:09.490 --> 01:28:13.860
that at any given moment, the
particle will have a mix--

01:28:13.860 --> 01:28:18.640
the system will have a mix
of kinetic energy and energy

01:28:18.640 --> 01:28:21.550
stored into the spring,
which is referred

01:28:21.550 --> 01:28:23.960
to as potential energy.

01:28:23.960 --> 01:28:27.270
So of course, the kinetic
energy is given by 1/2 times

01:28:27.270 --> 01:28:29.520
the mass times the
velocity squared.

01:28:29.520 --> 01:28:31.920
If you remember the
definition of momentum,

01:28:31.920 --> 01:28:35.050
momentum equals
mass times velocity.

01:28:35.050 --> 01:28:36.960
So I can also
write it like this.

01:28:36.960 --> 01:28:40.470
Momentum squared over
2 times the mass.

01:28:40.470 --> 01:28:41.910
And the potential energy--

01:28:41.910 --> 01:28:45.240
actually, the potential energy
can have very different forms

01:28:45.240 --> 01:28:49.500
depending on what is exactly
the energy storage element.

01:28:49.500 --> 01:28:50.960
In the case of a spring--

01:28:50.960 --> 01:28:54.230
actually, in the case of a
hook spring, a linear spring,

01:28:54.230 --> 01:28:58.110
it is simply equal to the
square of the displacement

01:28:58.110 --> 01:29:03.400
of the spring with respect
to its rest position.

01:29:03.400 --> 01:29:05.800
So anyway, no matter
what these things are,

01:29:05.800 --> 01:29:08.620
the sum must be
constant because, again,

01:29:08.620 --> 01:29:11.380
energy cannot be gained
or lost by its system.

01:29:11.380 --> 01:29:13.960
So the sum of the potential
and kinetic energy

01:29:13.960 --> 01:29:17.340
is always conserved.

01:29:17.340 --> 01:29:19.530
So that is one thing,
and it's very good.

01:29:22.250 --> 01:29:26.900
Now, let me play a game.

01:29:30.190 --> 01:29:38.595
So first of all, I
will write the energy.

01:29:38.595 --> 01:29:40.470
I will basically repeat
what is on the slide.

01:29:40.470 --> 01:29:44.100
I will repeat it on
the whiteboard here.

01:29:44.100 --> 01:29:45.658
So let me write the energy.

01:29:45.658 --> 01:29:46.950
I will write it in a funny way.

01:29:46.950 --> 01:29:52.430
I will write it as a function of
the momentum p and the position

01:29:52.430 --> 01:29:53.160
q.

01:29:53.160 --> 01:29:55.460
And now, in the
previous slide, these

01:29:55.460 --> 01:30:00.920
were actually scalar quantities
because this thing moves only

01:30:00.920 --> 01:30:03.180
along a straight line.

01:30:03.180 --> 01:30:07.130
But in general, of course, I
can have positions and momenta

01:30:07.130 --> 01:30:09.110
that are vectors.

01:30:09.110 --> 01:30:10.500
So I switched to
vector notation.

01:30:10.500 --> 01:30:13.880
I hope that doesn't
confuse you horribly.

01:30:13.880 --> 01:30:14.900
So let me write it down.

01:30:14.900 --> 01:30:20.510
So in the vector case, this
will equal the momentum vector

01:30:20.510 --> 01:30:27.020
divided by 2m plus 1/2 m--

01:30:27.020 --> 01:30:27.700
wait a minute.

01:30:27.700 --> 01:30:36.250
1/2 k, the spring constant,
times the position vector

01:30:36.250 --> 01:30:38.400
square.

01:30:38.400 --> 01:30:40.890
Now what I'm going
to do, for fun,

01:30:40.890 --> 01:30:45.000
is I'm going to take derivatives
of this quantity with respect

01:30:45.000 --> 01:30:48.270
to the position
and the momentum.

01:30:48.270 --> 01:30:50.340
Of course, since
these became vectors,

01:30:50.340 --> 01:30:52.080
now these are not
exactly derivatives,

01:30:52.080 --> 01:30:54.000
they are gradients.

01:30:54.000 --> 01:31:00.570
So basically what I will do is
I will compute the gradient of H

01:31:00.570 --> 01:31:01.830
with respect to p.

01:31:08.010 --> 01:31:09.240
This is a matter of notation.

01:31:09.240 --> 01:31:15.090
I will denote it as dH dp.

01:31:15.090 --> 01:31:16.440
So what is dH dp?

01:31:16.440 --> 01:31:24.600
Well, what I have to do
is I have to compute--

01:31:24.600 --> 01:31:28.620
clearly this term does not play
because it only depends on q.

01:31:28.620 --> 01:31:31.540
But this term
contains the momentum.

01:31:31.540 --> 01:31:33.970
So if I do it, it will
actually-- you can do it.

01:31:33.970 --> 01:31:38.770
It is actually p times its--

01:31:43.020 --> 01:31:44.900
p over m.

01:31:44.900 --> 01:31:45.400
That's it.

01:31:45.400 --> 01:31:45.942
Nothing else.

01:31:48.370 --> 01:31:54.038
And then I'm going to do
the same with respect to q.

01:31:56.970 --> 01:32:01.220
And I'm going to call it dH dq.

01:32:01.220 --> 01:32:04.130
Again, it is a gradient
with respect to q.

01:32:04.130 --> 01:32:06.050
And for the same reasons
as the other one,

01:32:06.050 --> 01:32:08.350
it will turn out
to be k times 2.

01:32:11.720 --> 01:32:12.220
OK.

01:32:12.220 --> 01:32:14.630
Then again for fun--

01:32:14.630 --> 01:32:16.980
I'm not justifying
what I'm doing.

01:32:16.980 --> 01:32:20.440
It's just coming sort of some--

01:32:20.440 --> 01:32:24.220
coming out of some
sort of epiphany.

01:32:24.220 --> 01:32:28.210
I will write down two
differential equations.

01:32:28.210 --> 01:32:30.540
One of them, I will
write this one.

01:32:30.540 --> 01:32:32.940
It is already on
your screen there.

01:32:32.940 --> 01:32:36.870
dq dt.

01:32:36.870 --> 01:32:37.830
What is that?

01:32:37.830 --> 01:32:40.730
That's the time derivative
of the displacement.

01:32:40.730 --> 01:32:43.140
Therefore, it is the velocity.

01:32:43.140 --> 01:32:51.870
So we'll take it to be equal
to the gradient of the quantity

01:32:51.870 --> 01:32:58.010
H of the energy, that we called
it H for some strange reason,

01:32:58.010 --> 01:33:00.020
with respect to the
opposite variable.

01:33:00.020 --> 01:33:01.655
This was the derivative of q.

01:33:01.655 --> 01:33:04.280
I will take its gradient
with respect to p.

01:33:07.620 --> 01:33:08.870
And let's see what I get.

01:33:08.870 --> 01:33:14.920
This way I get p over m.

01:33:14.920 --> 01:33:18.300
That's correct.

01:33:18.300 --> 01:33:22.540
Actually, this equation is
not particularly insightful.

01:33:22.540 --> 01:33:25.770
This is the definition
of momentum, isn't it?

01:33:25.770 --> 01:33:32.910
If you recall-- this means
recall, like in cartoons.

01:33:32.910 --> 01:33:36.200
The little cloud.

01:33:36.200 --> 01:33:43.410
The momentum is defined
as m times dq dt.

01:33:43.410 --> 01:33:45.750
That's the definition
of momentum.

01:33:45.750 --> 01:33:48.050
So by doing this
trick, by taking

01:33:48.050 --> 01:33:53.660
the gradient of the energy
with respect to the momentum

01:33:53.660 --> 01:34:00.920
and setting it equal to the
velocity, I got a true result.

01:34:00.920 --> 01:34:03.420
I got a result that
happens to be true.

01:34:03.420 --> 01:34:06.860
Now let's see if I can
pull the opposite trick.

01:34:06.860 --> 01:34:10.070
If I can take the
derivative with respect

01:34:10.070 --> 01:34:14.970
to time of the momentum, that's
like an acceleration quantity

01:34:14.970 --> 01:34:17.790
because momentum is velocity.

01:34:17.790 --> 01:34:20.170
So its derivative
is acceleration.

01:34:20.170 --> 01:34:22.610
And let's see if I can
get away by putting

01:34:22.610 --> 01:34:27.550
it equal to the derivative
of this quantity H

01:34:27.550 --> 01:34:29.770
with respect to
the other variable.

01:34:29.770 --> 01:34:32.170
In this case, I cannot
quite get away with it.

01:34:32.170 --> 01:34:35.620
I have to put a minus sign.

01:34:35.620 --> 01:34:37.460
And what do I get if
I put a minus sign?

01:34:37.460 --> 01:34:37.960
kq.

01:34:41.853 --> 01:34:42.520
What's this now?

01:34:48.510 --> 01:34:50.730
kq?

01:34:50.730 --> 01:34:54.020
It is k times displacement.

01:34:54.020 --> 01:34:59.020
So what are the units of Hooke's
constant time displacement?

01:34:59.020 --> 01:35:00.970
Force.

01:35:00.970 --> 01:35:02.220
What is on the left-hand side?

01:35:06.280 --> 01:35:06.780
OK.

01:35:06.780 --> 01:35:07.800
I said acceleration.

01:35:07.800 --> 01:35:09.840
Actually, I should
have corrected myself,

01:35:09.840 --> 01:35:13.120
and I should have said,
proportional to acceleration.

01:35:13.120 --> 01:35:15.220
This is the derivative
of the momentum.

01:35:15.220 --> 01:35:17.900
So therefore, it is force.

01:35:17.900 --> 01:35:19.980
So what is this then,
the equation that I got?

01:35:23.820 --> 01:35:26.960
It is the force balance on the--

01:35:26.960 --> 01:35:30.000
it is Newton's law,
actually, on the particle.

01:35:30.000 --> 01:35:34.170
It says that the force
pulling the particle,

01:35:34.170 --> 01:35:38.300
it is the restoring
force due to the spring.

01:35:38.300 --> 01:35:41.630
And what are the two
equations combined?

01:35:41.630 --> 01:35:43.650
Actually, the two
equations combined,

01:35:43.650 --> 01:35:47.020
they are what we call
the equations of motion.

01:35:47.020 --> 01:35:49.440
The equations of
motion, by definition,

01:35:49.440 --> 01:35:52.650
are first order
differential equations

01:35:52.650 --> 01:35:55.620
that link the dynamical
variables that

01:35:55.620 --> 01:36:00.250
is the position, the
displacement, and the velocity.

01:36:00.250 --> 01:36:01.270
So this is what I did.

01:36:01.270 --> 01:36:03.960
I got a set of
differential equations

01:36:03.960 --> 01:36:08.430
that link the displacement
to the momentum-- that

01:36:08.430 --> 01:36:09.540
is the velocity.

01:36:09.540 --> 01:36:14.370
And again, the derivative of
the displacement back to the--

01:36:14.370 --> 01:36:16.120
I'm sorry, the derivative
of the velocity,

01:36:16.120 --> 01:36:19.200
the derivative of the momentum,
back to the displacement

01:36:19.200 --> 01:36:21.120
itself.

01:36:21.120 --> 01:36:28.460
So if you look at it, if
you omit this middle part,

01:36:28.460 --> 01:36:31.210
if you look at it like
this, these are simply--

01:36:31.210 --> 01:36:34.600
as I said, these are
the equations of motion.

01:36:34.600 --> 01:36:39.630
If you look at this part
over here, this is of course

01:36:39.630 --> 01:36:42.950
a more general result. That's
why I bothered to do it.

01:36:42.950 --> 01:36:44.700
And this is where the
connection to optics

01:36:44.700 --> 01:36:46.980
will come from next week.

01:36:46.980 --> 01:36:50.550
This set of equations
is called Hamiltonian.

01:36:54.940 --> 01:36:58.190
And I will put in
brackets "canonical."

01:36:58.190 --> 01:36:59.790
I don't particularly
like this term.

01:36:59.790 --> 01:37:01.970
But anyway, some people use it.

01:37:01.970 --> 01:37:05.539
Hamiltonian canonical equations.

01:37:10.030 --> 01:37:12.410
So the point, then, which
I will say just this,

01:37:12.410 --> 01:37:14.760
and then I will stop
and continue next time,

01:37:14.760 --> 01:37:18.200
the point is that this is now
a much more general property.

01:37:18.200 --> 01:37:22.400
Even though I showed that it
is true for the specific case

01:37:22.400 --> 01:37:26.450
of a mass spring
system without damper--

01:37:26.450 --> 01:37:27.800
I showed that to be true.

01:37:27.800 --> 01:37:30.260
But this is a more
general property

01:37:30.260 --> 01:37:36.630
for any dynamical system that
has a conserved quantity.

01:37:36.630 --> 01:37:38.460
So in the case of the
mechanical system,

01:37:38.460 --> 01:37:40.900
the conserved
quantity is energy.

01:37:40.900 --> 01:37:42.670
If this conserved
quantity can be

01:37:42.670 --> 01:37:46.540
written as a function of
the dynamical variables,

01:37:46.540 --> 01:37:52.010
in this case, of the mechanical
system position and momentum--

01:37:52.010 --> 01:37:52.510
OK.

01:37:52.510 --> 01:37:54.880
So I started a long sentence.

01:37:54.880 --> 01:37:57.460
Let me close my sentence.

01:37:57.460 --> 01:38:02.170
So if a dynamical system
has a conserved quantity,

01:38:02.170 --> 01:38:07.880
then I can write down a set
of Hamiltonian equations

01:38:07.880 --> 01:38:09.770
for this dynamical
system in terms

01:38:09.770 --> 01:38:13.280
of the gradients of
this conserved quantity.

01:38:13.280 --> 01:38:16.490
And that will be the
equations of motion.

01:38:16.490 --> 01:38:17.520
OK.

01:38:17.520 --> 01:38:20.270
So what we will
do then next time

01:38:20.270 --> 01:38:23.120
is we will actually
show, in almost one

01:38:23.120 --> 01:38:25.340
to one analogy, that--

01:38:25.340 --> 01:38:27.470
oh, and by the way,
this conserved quantity

01:38:27.470 --> 01:38:30.890
that we called it energy in the
case of the mechanical system,

01:38:30.890 --> 01:38:33.410
in general it's called
the Hamiltonian.

01:38:33.410 --> 01:38:38.540
So H itself is the Hamiltonian.

01:38:38.540 --> 01:38:40.460
So what we'll do next
is we will actually

01:38:40.460 --> 01:38:47.060
show we can derive a Hamiltonian
for rays for an optical system.

01:38:47.060 --> 01:38:50.600
And of course, when we write
equations of motion for rays,

01:38:50.600 --> 01:38:53.550
we'll get the ray trajectories.

01:38:53.550 --> 01:38:55.483
Therefore, we will be
able to ray tracing.

01:38:55.483 --> 01:38:56.900
And the reason
this is interesting

01:38:56.900 --> 01:39:00.410
because the potential
actually will turn out

01:39:00.410 --> 01:39:02.670
to be the index of refraction.

01:39:02.670 --> 01:39:05.630
And in the same way,
the potential here,

01:39:05.630 --> 01:39:08.540
if you go back to my equation--

01:39:08.540 --> 01:39:12.930
the potential turned out to
be a function of position.

01:39:12.930 --> 01:39:16.860
In the gradient index optics
that we mentioned just now,

01:39:16.860 --> 01:39:19.820
the index of refraction
is a function of position.

01:39:19.820 --> 01:39:23.820
So we will see that in the
case of the GRIN element,

01:39:23.820 --> 01:39:27.000
the index of refraction actually
has the role of a potential.

01:39:27.000 --> 01:39:29.050
And it is this potential
that draws the--

01:39:29.050 --> 01:39:30.750
very similar to gravity.

01:39:30.750 --> 01:39:32.850
The potential that
draws the sun--

01:39:32.850 --> 01:39:36.630
I mean, that draws the Earth to
rotate around the sun and not

01:39:36.630 --> 01:39:38.350
the other way around.

01:39:38.350 --> 01:39:40.560
The same way the
potential draws the Earth

01:39:40.560 --> 01:39:43.710
to rotate around the
sun, it is a similar,

01:39:43.710 --> 01:39:46.170
or I should say analogous,
kind of potential

01:39:46.170 --> 01:39:49.980
that draws rays inwards
in a GRIN element

01:39:49.980 --> 01:39:53.610
and causes them to focus.

01:39:53.610 --> 01:39:57.820
So we'll pick up
on that next time.

